          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>In dem Meeserschen Hause<lb/> über der
                                                  Brücke<lb/> am Neckar <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >Heidelberg</hi></placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <date>March 9<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1854</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>Dear friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">I am taking the opportunity<lb/> of writing a
                                        little to you by a Gentleman<lb/> about to leave
                                                  <placeName>Heidelberg</placeName> for
                                                  <placeName>New York</placeName>. I<lb/> have not
                                        your correct address here; I<lb/> therefore must trust to
                                        his kindness in<lb/> sending it safely to you at
                                                  <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.<lb/> When I
                                        last heard from my dear family<lb/> one of my sisters wrote
                                        to say that the “<hi rend="underline">Occident</hi>”<lb/>
                                        had been sent to me in
                                                  <placeName>Baker<add>?</add></placeName> in which
                                        they read<lb/> a <hi rend="underline">beautiful</hi> notice
                                        of my Poems from<lb/> your gifted mind, with some
                                        pieces<lb/> transcribed. I assure you I appreciate<lb/>
                                        <hi rend="underline">much</hi> your kindness also for
                                        the<lb/> advertisement therein—my sisters have<lb/>
                                        requested two more copies to be sent<lb/> for them &amp; I
                                        am to receive <hi rend="underline">my</hi><lb/> number in
                                                  <date>May</date>, when <persName>Mr
                                                  Simon's</persName><lb/> family are going to visit
                                        us, en route</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>for <placeName>Switzerland</placeName>.</p>
                              <p>I presume from this circumstance<lb/> that the books arrived safely
                                        at their<lb/> destination—&amp; that you have long<lb/>
                                        since obtained your <hi rend="underline">own</hi>
                                        rightful<lb/> copy. I hope also that my long letter<lb/>
                                        reached you from the “<add>?</add>” where<lb/> we then
                                        resided. I wrote your address<lb/> quite from guess, for I
                                        left my Occidents<lb/> with all my principal books to
                                        be<lb/> taken charge of.</p>
                              <p>My dear friend <persName>Miss Brettell<add>?</add></persName> has
                                        taken<lb/> with me these charming rooms facing<lb/> the
                                        Castle &amp; <placeName>Neckar</placeName> where we
                                        have<lb/> not only a most romantic picture<lb/> ever before
                                        our eyes, but also every comfort<lb/> &amp; convenience in
                                        this beautiful House.<lb/> My <hi rend="underline">good</hi>
                                        Papa at length yielded to my<lb/> longing wish for a more
                                                  <hi rend="underline">country</hi> life &amp;<lb/>
                                        now permits me to follow my inclination<del>s</del><lb/>
                                        which was never in favor of a residence<lb/> in our gay
                                        &amp; busy city of <placeName>London</placeName>!</p>
                              <p>It is, as you may imagine, an infinite<lb/> blessing to me thus to
                                        enjoy, in more<lb/> retirement, the glorious beauties of
                                        nature,<lb/> &amp; my own favorite studies of Literature
                                        &amp;<lb/> music. I do not know yet how long we<lb/> may
                                        remain in <placeName>Heidelberg</placeName>. I think we<lb/>
                                        shall spend <date>June</date> &amp; <date>July</date> in
                                                  <placeName>Switzerland</placeName><lb/> (my 3d
                                        visit) &amp; then most likely go to<lb/>
                                        <placeName>England</placeName> for a few months as we
                                        shall<lb/> both be <sic>anscious</sic> to see our friends
                                        there.</p>
                              <p>We have had a <hi rend="underline">very</hi> severe winter,
                                        but<lb/> to <hi rend="underline">me</hi> the charm has been
                                        so great<lb/> that I could not regret it. To see the<lb/>
                                        scenery here all enveloped in its <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >snowy</hi><lb/> mantle—has been a continual
                                        source<lb/> of enjoyment to me &amp; the tinkling<lb/> bells
                                        of the horses as they bore the gay<lb/> sledges along, did
                                        not a little enhance the<lb/> beauty of the picture!</p>
                              <p>I suppose you hear as much of<lb/> the War as we do. Some
                                        people<lb/> are of opinion that it is the first</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>step towards the restoration of our<lb/> Nation—according to the
                                        Prophecies.<lb/> What is your opinion? And how<lb/> goes on
                                        your interesting work, the Bible?</p>
                              <p>Have you heard of a <hi rend="underline">small</hi> book<lb/>
                                        published in <date>1853</date> at Chapman's in the<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Strand, London</placeName> (price 36 s. d.) “<hi
                                                  rend="underline">A few words to</hi><lb/>
                                        <hi rend="underline">the Jews</hi>”? It is splendidly
                                        written,<lb/> &amp; most touchingly beautiful—<lb/> We, as
                                        Israelites, cannot be too grateful<lb/> to God for raising
                                        amongst us such<lb/> an Author—so deeply imbued with the
                                        true<lb/> spirit of Judaism. I hope it will soon<lb/> be
                                        well known both in <placeName>England</placeName> &amp;
                                                  <placeName>America</placeName>.<lb/> We do not
                                        know the name of the Author<lb/> not his place of abode—he
                                        merely adds<lb/> in the title page “by one of
                                        themselves.”<lb/> Surely he will one day be known!<lb/> at
                                        present all is in mystery respecting the<lb/> books. My
                                        paper tells me to say farewell<lb/> for the present, &amp;
                                        trusting you are in<lb/> good health, I remain dear
                                        friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Your's sincerely, <persName role="author">Rosa
                                                  <add>?</add> Salsman</persName></p>
